        <!-- Project Overview -->
        <div class="project-section">
            <h3>Project Overview</h3>
            <p>
                This project demonstrates using <strong>Terraform</strong> to provision cloud infrastructure. 
                A single <code>main.tf</code> configuration file was used to define and deploy an <strong>EC2 instance</strong> in AWS. 
                By following the Terraform workflow, the deployment process was fully automated and repeatable.
            </p>
        </div>

        <!-- Architecture -->
        <div class="project-section alt-bg">
            <h3>Architecture Explanation</h3>
            <p>The architecture of this project includes:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Terraform CLI</strong> – Executes commands to interact with AWS.</li>
                <li><strong>AWS Provider</strong> – Connects Terraform to the AWS API using credentials.</li>
                <li><strong>main.tf</strong> – Defines the EC2 instance (AMI, instance type, key pair, region).</li>
                <li><strong>EC2 Instance</strong> – Launched automatically in the AWS account.</li>
                <li><strong>User</strong> – Connects to the instance via SSH or uses the public IP.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Key Learnings -->
        <div class="project-section">
            <h3>Key Learnings</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Learned the Terraform workflow: <code>init → validate → plan → apply → destroy</code>.</li>
                <li>Defined infrastructure using HCL (HashiCorp Configuration Language).</li>
                <li>Compared Infrastructure as Code with manual AWS Console provisioning.</li>
                <li>Understood the importance of state files in Terraform for tracking resources.</li>
                <li>Appreciated how IaC improves repeatability, speed, and collaboration.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Best Practices -->
        <div class="project-section alt-bg">
            <h3>Notes & Best Practices</h3>
            <p>
                For simplicity, this project created a single EC2 instance. In real-world production setups:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Use <strong>variables.tf</strong> to avoid hardcoding credentials or values.</li>
                <li>Store state files remotely in <strong>S3 with DynamoDB</strong> for team collaboration.</li>
                <li>Organize configurations using <strong>modules</strong> for reusability.</li>
                <li>Combine Terraform with CI/CD tools (AWS CodePipeline, Jenkins, GitHub Actions).</li>
                <li>Never commit AWS access keys to version control; use environment variables or IAM roles.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

